<br>
One thing that I don't like about American history teaching is the idea that our dropping the Bomb on Nagasaki and Hiroshima was the sole reason that Japan surrendered.  It was only part (although significant) of the reasoning, with the Russians massing at Vladivostok to be a part of Operation Coronet, the invasion plan for the Japanese Mainland, being another significant part.  Surrendering to the US was a better choice for the Japanese, since the Japanese knew the Russians were wanting payback for the Russo-Japanese war<br>
<br>
However, you can't discount the impact the Lend-Lease Act had on the Allies.  There's a reason why the US got the name &quot;Arsenal of Democracy&quot; and Canada didn't.  The Russians would have had a much harder time without American machine tools they used to make so much of their war machine with after they moved their war production to the safety of Siberia. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=187084"><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Colphax Moonleaf</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
